**M1 — Asserted interfaces are not derived from implementation types**

Every new interface (`CronResult`, `QuotaResetResult`, `TrialExpiryResult`, etc.) is hand-written in the test file and applied via a bare `as TypeName` assertion on the handler result. TypeScript treats `as` as an unconditional override — if the underlying Inngest handler ever changes its return shape (renames a field, adds a required key, changes optionality) the assertion will still compile cleanly while tests silently read `undefined`.

Preferred fix: export the return type from the implementation and use it in the test:

```ts
// monthly-report-cron.ts (implementation)
export type CronResult = Awaited<ReturnType<typeof monthlyReportCronFn>>;

// monthly-report-cron.test.ts
import type { CronResult } from './monthly-report-cron';
```

If the implementation uses `(handler as any).fn` making the return type uninferable, a minimum safeguard is a JSDoc comment on each interface stating it was manually audited against the source — so future readers know the shape is a confirmed contract, not a guess.

---

**Accommodation screen redirects legitimate owners during profile load**

File: apps/mobile/src/app/(app)/more/accommodation.tsx, lines 80-84

The useEffect fires as soon as `isChildMode && !canEditChildPreferences`. During the initial render, activeProfile is null (profile query still loading), so canEditChildPreferences evaluates to false even for a legitimate owner. The effect immediately replaces the route with /(app)/more before profile data arrives.

Fix: destructure isLoading from useProfile() and gate the redirect on it:

```ts
const { activeProfile, profiles, isLoading } = useProfile();
// ...
useEffect(() => {
  if (!isLoading && isChildMode && !canEditChildPreferences) {
    router.replace(route);
  }
}, [isLoading, canEditChildPreferences, isChildMode, router]);
```

(where `route` is `'/(app)/more' as never`)

---

**2. handleSaveAndQuit is a silent no-op when auto-save is already in flight**

File: apps/mobile/src/app/(app)/quiz/play.tsx, lines 241-244

When the last question is answered, submitRound({ navigateOnSuccess: false }) fires automatically and sets roundSubmittedRef.current = true. If the user opens the quit dialog during that save and taps "Save and Finish", handleSaveAndQuit calls submitRound() which hits the roundSubmittedRef.current guard and silently returns. The modal closes but nothing navigates — the user appears stuck with no feedback.

Minimal fix: detect in-flight state and let roundAutoSaved drive the UI:

```ts
const handleSaveAndQuit = () => {
  if (resultsRef.current.length === 0) return;
  setQuitConfirmVisible(false);
  if (roundSubmittedRef.current) {
    return; // auto-save in flight; UI will update via roundAutoSaved
  }
  submitRound();
};
```

**3. gc1-allow annotation is inside the factory body, not on the jest.mock() line**

File: apps/mobile/src/app/(app)/child/[profileId]/_layout.test.tsx, lines 30-32

CLAUDE.md rule: "append // gc1-allow: reason on the same line as the jest.mock( call". The annotation here is a standalone comment inside the factory; the GC1 ratchet scans for it on the jest.mock( line. Correct form (matching every other use in this PR):

```ts
jest.mock(
  '../../../../lib/theme' /* gc1-allow: theme hook requires native ColorScheme unavailable in JSDOM */,
  () => ({
    useThemeColors: () => ({ background: BGCOLOR }),
  }),
);
```

(where `BGCOLOR` is `'#000'`)

